    "what_description": "Sedum caffrum is a succulent plant species belonging to the family Crassulaceae. It is characterized by its small, flat rosettes of densely packed leaves, typically 3-6 cm in diameter, with a short, stout stem. The leaves are glaucous, green, and sometimes tinged with yellow or red, with a leathery texture and a wavy margin. Sedum caffrum produces small, white or yellow flowers in summer, arranged in a lax inflorescence on a 10-20 cm tall stem. The plant is native to the southwestern part of the Eastern Cape Province in South Africa, where it grows in well-drained, rocky soil in full sun.",
